issue_comments.body:
I like the TypeDeterminator name you suggest for the interface. I'm not a native English speaker and coming up with good names isn't always easy.

I think your suggestion is on a higher level of abstraction (as it hides the type determination), but is actually _less_ general than mine. For example, it won't be able to directly handle legacy data. You'll have to first add this additional attribute to all items, and this may not always work.

That said, I don't see why we can't have both.

A somewhat manual way to implement your proposal on top of mine would be to:
- Add a determinant attribute to the base of the persistent hierarchy:

``` java
class User {
    @DynamoDBAttribute(attributeName = "determinant")
    public String getDeterminant() { return getClass().getCannonicalName(); }
}
```
- Use a TypeDeterminator which just loads the named class.

I'm not sure how to make the first step more elegant. Probably some specialized annotation?

